# Alpha memo: AI agents, tool use, verification, and reliability

## Core signal
Two 2025 RAG studies in the *medical* domain independently target the same bottleneck — *retrieval result quality* (rank, density, context length) — as the lever for trustworthiness. Receipt 1 proposes BriefContext, a map-reduce workflow to combat "lost-in-the-middle" without weight changes, promising reduced misinformation and safer LLM deployment in medical QA/clinical decision support. Receipt 2 builds multiple RAG variants (naïve, LOTR-RAG, CRAG, SRAG) on top of GPT-4 over a ~130,000-paper COVID-19 corpus to fact-check claims and address hallucination and context inaccuracy.

## The 2+2=5 angle
Both receipts equate *more retrieval* with *more reliability*, yet they share an unstated tension: Receipt 1 admits relevance/rank of retrieved evidence drives RAG quality, while Receipt 2's reliance on ~130,000 peer-reviewed papers means a relevant-but-contradictory or stale study can be "relevantly retrieved" and still yield a confidently wrong answer. The bridge term "relevance" is doing two different jobs — top-k similarity to the prompt (Receipt 2) vs. preservation of critical snippets across long context (Receipt 1). If you naively combine map-reduce (Receipt 1) with a 130k-paper vector store (Receipt 2), you may optimize *internal* snippet retention while *worsening* the external evidence pool's failure modes (citation rot, retracted COVID-19 papers, paywalled corrections). The negative/positive flip: a "more reliable" pipeline can quietly become a higher-confidence misinformation amplifier in fast-moving clinical domains.

## Why this could matter
For investors and builders, the RAG reliability narrative is anchored to a metric mismatch — chunk-level retrieval scores ≠ claim-level fact accuracy. The COVID-19 fact-checking framing in Receipt 2 also shows the *tool-use* layer (vector store, CRAG, self-RAG) is now the verification primitive, not a downstream filter. A hypothesis: tooling that exposes retrieval provenance + recency + retraction status will be the binding constraint, not model quality.

## What would break the idea
- If BriefContext-style workflows fail to outperform weighted fine-tuning on clinical QA benchmarks.
- If COVID-19-style fact-checking RAG systems show positive accuracy deltas only on retrospective, not real-time, claim streams.
- Any generalisation beyond medical QA/fact-checking remains a hypothesis.

## Receipts
- 10.1038/s41746-025-01651-w — trial/protocol: BriefContext map-reduce RAG for medical QA.
- 10.2196/66098 — case study: GPT-4 RAG variants for COVID-19 fact-checking over ~130k-paper corpus.

## Safety note
Receipts are medical-domain studies; relevance signals are not validated for combat, political, or general misinformation settings. Treat cross-domain transfer as a hypothesis.

